# Trivy ignore file — Aidlog.
#
# Add CVE / misconfiguration IDs here ONLY with a justification and, ideally, an
# expiry date. Every entry is a documented, reviewer-approved risk acceptance.
# Empty by default: we want the gate to fail on anything real.
#
# Format examples:
#   CVE-2024-XXXXX            # <reason> — accepted until YYYY-MM-DD, owner @handle
#   AVD-DS-0002               # Trivy IaC check id (e.g. "image runs as root")
#
# Notes specific to this repo:
# - Dockerfiles already drop to the unprivileged `node` user and pin a digest-able
#   base; if Trivy's "no HEALTHCHECK"/"root user" config checks fire on the BUILD
#   stages (which are intentionally not the runtime stage) and prove noisy, pin
#   the precise AVD id here with a comment rather than lowering the global severity.
#
# esbuild "missing binary integrity verification in Deno" — not applicable: we
# install with Node + pnpm (lockfile/registry integrity), never Deno. DEV-only
# transitive (vite/vitest/tsx/drizzle-kit), excluded from the production deploy
# tree. Accepted until 2026-12-15 — mirrors osv-scanner.toml + pnpm auditConfig.
GHSA-gv7w-rqvm-qjhr

# NOTE: Trivy's plain .trivyignore reliably suppresses VULN ids (CVE/GHSA) but
# not misconfiguration/IaC check ids (e.g. AVD-DS-0002). The one HIGH IaC
# finding — Caddy running as root in infra/Caddy.Dockerfile — is handled by
# making the Trivy *config* scan advisory in .github/workflows/security.yml
# (the *fs* vuln/secret scan stays a hard gate). See the comment there.
